TI  - Effective production of sodium isobutyl xanthate using carbon disulfide as a solvent: Reaction kinetics, calorimetry and scale-up
VL  - 200
SP  - 444-453
AB  - Alkyl xanthates are by far the most widely used collectors in the froth flotation beneficiation of base metal sulfide and precious metal ores. However, the commercial xanthate production process suffers from low yield, low productivity, poor containment and environmental pollution. To address these issues, an effective method was developed for the synthesis of xanthates using carbon disulfide as both a reactant and the solvent. This study involved the optimization of various process parameters, including solvent dosage, temperature, caustic alkali particle size, and agitation speed, to intensify the conversion of sodium isobutyl xanthate (SIBX) and elucidate the reaction kinetics. The results indicated that carbon disulfide leads to a higher yield and better purity than solvents such as dichloromethane, petroleum ether, acetone, and water. Moreover, the addition of solvent allows the synthesis of high-purity xanthates by employing commercial grainy/sheet caustic soda as the raw material without further pulverization. The rate of the xanthation reaction was controlled by the rate of diffusion through the product layer, and the apparent activation energy was calculated to be 15 kJ.mol(-1). In addition, the thermal behavior of xanthate synthesis in a medium was monitored in a 2 L reaction calorimeter (RC1e) under the optimal conditions. Finally, a pilot-plant process was conducted in a 4000 L stainless-steel-jacketed reactor. The results demonstrated that xanthate production using excess carbon disulfide as a self-solvent gave excellent yield (>95%) and purity (>90%), whereas the kneader approach provided SIBX in only a 91% yield and 84% purity. Furthermore, this technology has widespread adaptability for the preparation of C-2 to C-8 xanthates. Compared with the traditional kneader approach, this new synthesis technology completely eliminates the required pulverization of caustic alkali, intensifies mass and heat transfer via the solvent, raises the productivity and improves the manufacturing environment, offering an effective and promising approach for the clean production of xanthates. (C) 2018 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
