AB  - The diversity of plants and animals at high altitudes is well studied, but there are scarcity of reports on diversity of microorganisms and their networking with plants. Extreme environments at high altitude have a very high impact on inhabiting plants and microbes. Here is an effort to explore the relationship between plant, microbes and environmental conditions at high altitude. The composition of microbial communities at high altitude, shaping the abundance and distribution, depends on the extreme environmental factors such as cold and hypoxia. Microorganisms have a range of adaptations that allow them to remain active in the extreme environments of high altitude and are indispensable for their survival. The extreme freezing temperature present at high altitude affects the microbial cells in many ways such as decrease in membrane fluidity, decrease in ribosome efficiency, and increased stabilization of secondary structures of nucleic acids. Collectively these factors may affect DNA replication, transcription and translation and leads to physiological and evolutionary adaptations. Similarly the plants present in any given environment influence everything from food chain to climate change. High altitude environment influence a plants physiology and morphology in many ways that may change their interaction with microorganism. The present chapter summarizes current knowledge about the ubiquitous presence of microbes and plants at high altitude atmosphere and various evolutionary and physiological adaptations required for survival. The purpose is to evaluate the high altitude environment as a source of pathogenic and beneficial interaction between microbes and plants. © 2017 by Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.
